    <div id="tribute-info">
      <p>In what was billed as the biggest Premier League game in years, Arsenal’s defeat on Sunday against title rivals Manchester City could prove to be a fatal blow to their hopes of ending an agonising 22-year wait for football glory.
Arsenal appeared to have one hand on the English Premier League trophy for months, but City are now just three points behind them, with momentum and a game in hand when they face Burnley on Wednesday.</p>

      <h2>Years Bottled (Runner up 10 times)</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>2025/26</strong> - Led the league for 265+ days but fell away after a late-season slump. </li>
        <li><strong>2024/25</strong> - Finished second to a resurgent Liverpool side.</li>
        <li><strong>2023/24</strong> - Took the title race to the final day but finished 2 points behind City. </li>
        <li><strong>2022/23</strong> - Led the league for 248 days but fell away after a late-season slump. </li>
        <li><strong>2015/16</strong> - Finished as "best of the rest" behind the 5,000-1 miracle winners. </li>
        <li><strong>2004/05</strong> - 	Finished 12 points behind Jose Mourinho's record-breaking debut side. </li>
        <li><strong>2002/03</strong> -	Blew an 8-point lead in March to gift the title to Sir Alex Ferguson. </li>
        <li><strong>2000/01</strong> - The third of three straight runner-up finishes behind United.. </li>
        <li><strong>1999/00</strong> - 	Finished a massive 18 points behind a dominant United. </li>
        <li><strong>1989/99</strong> - Lost the title by just 1 point on the final day of the season. </li>
      </ul>

      <p>Arsenal holds the record for the most runner-up finishes in Premier League history (10). While these seasons highlight a remarkable level of consistency at the top of English football, they also underscore the narrow margins and late-season pressures that have often seen the Gunners fall just short of the ultimate prize. In conclusion, they are just shit.</p>

      

